<subSubSection id="BACF082D198269BDA7D08915B4117C2E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="4E9B9C6332E4DFD73B61C765BCE1D90B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B34B693777036A7ADB185603BF2BDDC3" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This species holds together despite the varied habit because of its broadly oblong to oblong-elliptic leaves which are usually undulate to crenate on the margins and because of the usually branched inflorescence. In related species the flowers are solitary-very rarely paired in 
<emphasis id="5A0CC474698AB0536EC66E096F3B6679" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="7ADC0D96827EE7C9B56F2941235A8651" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="procumbens">I. procumbens</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Erect specimens cited above are indicated with an asterisk*; unmarked collections are of decumbent plants.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="828E13FC66CFBD7F128BC29360F0B81A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="108E358E38EFC2CBE57A1911844F6818" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Queiroz et al.</emphasis>
5218 (K, HUEFS) from Bahia is odd as the inflorescence is on lateral branches with flowers mostly arising in the axils of distinct bracts resembling small leaves.
</paragraph>
